{{Infobox college |name = Center for Energy Research/Education/Service |parent = [[Ball State University]] |image = [[File:BSUArchBuilding.jpg|frameless]] |caption = The Center for Energy Research/Education/Service and [[Ball State University College of Architecture and Planning]]. CERES is the all glass part of the building |type = Center/Institute |established = 1982 |location = North of University Green |coor = {{coord|40.204517|-85.407007|region:US-IN_scale:1000|display=inline,title}} |director = Robert Koester |website = {{url|http://cms.bsu.edu/academics/centersandinstitutes/ceres}} |city=}}
The Ball State '''Center for Energy Research/Education/Service (CERES)''' is an interdisciplinary academic support unit at [[Ball State University]] focused on enhancing research and education on issues of energy usage and conservation. The center was established in 1982 as an addition to the existing [[Ball State University College of Architecture and Planning|College of Architecture and Planning]]. The center currently states the following as its mission: "To maintain ongoing programs for the examination of state-of-the-art energy conservation and end-use practices; To investigate alternative solutions to contemporary energy problems; To develop projections and implications of the results of these solutions; To devise means of implementing these ideas; To disseminate findings to the appropriate publics—professionals, educators, policy planners, students and laypersons."<ref>{{cite web|title=CERES, Center for Energy Research/Education/Service|url=http://cms.bsu.edu/academics/centersandinstitutes/ceres|accessdate=April 5, 2018|website=[[Ball State University|BSU.edu]]}}</ref>
==History== Concerns about environmentalism and conservation became popularized in the 1970s following the successes of the inaugural [[Earth Day]] that allowed for a sort of fusion between radical counterculture ideas regarding environmentalism and more mainstream ideas presented by politicians such as [[Gaylord Nelson]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Adam|last=Rome|author-link=Adam Rome|date=2013|title=The Genius of Earth Day: How a 1970 Teach-In Unexpectedly Made the First Green Generation|location=[[New York City|New York]]|publisher=[[Hill and Wang]]|isbn=9780809040506}}</ref> In addition, energy crises, such as the [[1973 Oil Crisis]] and the 1979 [[Three Mile Island accident]] caused concern about the way contemporary energy sources were being utilized, prompting some to begin research in alternative forms of energy or better forms of energy conservation.<ref>{{cite book|first=Robert|last=Gottlieb|date=2005|title=Forcing the Spring: The Transformation of the American Environmental Movement|location=[[Washington DC]]|publisher=[[Island Press]]|isbn=1559638052}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Hal K.|last=Rothman|author-link=Hal Rothman|date=1998|title=The Greening of a Nation? Environmentalism in the United States Since 1945|location=[[Fort Worth, Texas|Forth Worth]]|publisher=[[Harcourt Brace College Publishers]]|isbn=0155028553}}</ref> In response, Ball State University started their efforts to implement energy education into the college; in 1979, with funding from the [[Indiana General Assembly]], the university began planning of the Center for Energy Research/Education/Service, with construction beginning in the summer of 1980.<ref>{{cite report|first=Michael|last=Beattie|title=CERES: The Facility|url=http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/CERESPubs/id/499/rec/30|publisher=Ball State University Center for Energy Research/Education/Service|accessdate=April 5, 2018|location=[[Muncie, Indiana]]}}</ref> Simultaneously, [[Ball State University]] began planning for incorporating this sort of education about conservation and energy education into their curriculum, including proposed courses in environmental architecture and in utilizing [[solar energy]].<ref>{{cite report|title=Designing the Future: Comprehensive Planning for Energy Education and Research Group|date=November 1980|publisher=[[Ball State University]]}}</ref> In 1982, CERES was completed and opened for usage for Ball State's campus.
Since its inception in Ball State's campus, CERES has served as a means to incorporate energy education into Ball State's campus. By 1986, even, this had become one of its missions, with the Center becoming focused on placing Ball State as a leader in reaching a "sustainable future."<ref>{{cite report|title=Continued Implementation of a Sustainable Future: The 86/87 Plan|date=December 2, 1985|publisher=Ball State University Center for Energy Research/Education/Service}}</ref> The Center also had national significance; from the period between 1985 and 1988, CERES was one of only five test laboratories accredited by the Solar Rating and Certification Corporation for their solar research.<ref>{{cite report|title=A Ten-Year Synopsis|publisher=Ball State University Center for Energy Research/Education/Service|date=1992|accessdate=April 5, 2018|url=http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/CERESPubs/id/115/rec/2}}</ref> Going forward, the center has remained an integral part of energy and conservation research and education, both on Ball State's campus and in the greater [[Muncie, Indiana|Muncie]] community.
