{{Infobox writer | name = Elizabeth Marney Conner | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = ELIZABETH MARNEY CONNER.jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = Paul Veronique | birth_name = Elizabeth Marney | birth_date = February 26, 1856 | birth_place = [[Rouses Point, New York]], U.S. | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = Elmwood Cemetery, Burlington, Vermont | occupation = dramatic reader, educator | language = English | nationality = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = Marcus A. Conner | partner = | children = | years_active = | module = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} '''Elizabeth Marney Conner''' ([[pen name]] '''Paul Veronique'''; February 26, 1856 – ?) was a 19th-century American dramatic reader and educator, and the founder of the [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] School of [[Elocution]]. She published recitations in both prose and verse, and was also the author of an [[operetta]].
==Early years and education== Elizabeth Marney was born in [[Rouses Point, New York]], February 26, 1856.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=200}}
==Career== At the age of 18, she married Marcus A. Conner, of [[Burlington, Vermont]],{{sfn|Moulton|1890|p=18}} who died in 1881 in a drowning accident,<ref>{{cite news|title=Shocking Fatality|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12428088/shocking_fatality_the_burlington_free/|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[The Burlington Free Press]]''|date=9 July 1881|location=Burlington, Vermont|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> leaving her with two young sons to care for and educate. It was then Conner began to consider her ambitions. With decided abilities for music, literature and the drama, circumstances led her to choose some form of dramatic work, and she began the careful study of elocution. In January, 1884, the [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] School of Elocution and Literature was opened by Conner,{{sfn|Moulton|1890|p=18}} and after then, she rapidly succeeded as teacher and artist in her profession, having gained for herself and school an enviable local reputation, and being well-known in a far wider territory. Her lecture on "Expression" with illustrative readings was in demand from school, pulpit and platform.
She published recitations in both prose and verse under the pen-name "Paul Veronique," a strong poem, "Death of Samson". She also composed a song entitled "Be not so Sure", which was well received,{{sfn|Werner's Magazine Company|1894|p=112}} and was also the author of the operetta "Eulalie, a Fairy Operetta in Two Acts, for Children" (libretto by Conner, music by Mary M. Howard).{{sfn|Werner's Magazine|1887|p=36}} Although her success as a teacher and reader was exceptional, it was considered by many that her true place was on the stage. She had a strong personality and magnetic presence, intense dramatic fervor, a fine voice and versatile powers of expression.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=200}}
==Buffalo School of Elocution and Literature== Conner came to Buffalo with the object of establishing a training school of elocution and English literature. She made arrangements with the [[Young Men's Christian Association|YMCA]], and secured the necessary rooms for her venture before the outside doors were on the new building, which was nearing completion. The Buffalo School of Elocution and Literature was opened on the January 10, 1884, and was, from the beginning, a success. Establishing an institution of learning in a large city necessitated long hours; but the results were exemplary.{{sfn|Moulton|1888|p=307}}
The methods employed by Conner were far advanced than any ever before attempted in Buffalo. The physical and vocal drill class was a novelty, and was, from the first, highly prized by the students. The vocal practice eradicated all nasal, shrill, and guttural tones, while the [[François Delsarte|Delsarte]] method of exercising every muscle of the frame was beneficial to the body. As a preliminary to graduation from the Training School of Elocution, each pupil was required to give a public reading, the audience consisting of invited friends. These entertainments, in Association Hall, afforded a literary treat to the audience, and were an index of the accomplishments to be achieved by a course of study in such a school and under a teacher whose refining influence left an indelible impression on the pupil.{{sfn|Moulton|1888|p=307}}
At the close of the second year of the school, three pupils were graduated with honor. One became a teacher of elocution in the Buffalo High School. Another was for a long time associated with Conner in the school work. The third became a professional reader. On the completion of the third year, three more pupils received diplomas. One of that number, subsequently received the degree of Bachelor of Oratory at the Monroe School in [[Boston]]. The following year witnessed the graduation of six more pupils, some of whom became employed in the theatrical profession, in lecturing, reading, and teaching. Seven pupils were graduated in the class of 1888, and a larger number of juniors received certificates than at any previous year. Aside from the graduates' and postgraduates' recitals, the school gave frequent entertainments, such as "Shakespeare" and "Longfellow" afternoons, "Dickens," "Bryant,"' and "Whittier" evenings. Special lectures were given in connection with the regular course of study.{{sfn|Moulton|1888|p=307}}
Owing to the constant increase of business, it became necessary for Conner to seek larger and more commodious quarters than the WMCA building afforded. A new location, located at the junction of Mohawk, Genesee and Pearl streets, was secured. It was enlarged by establishing a second department, the Conservatory of Music under the able direction of Mary M. Howard, of Buffalo.{{sfn|Moulton|1888|p=307}} After operating the school for more than a decade, Conner left Buffalo in 1898 to give elocution recitals on a tour of the Pacific coast.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Social Chronicle|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201898%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201898%2520-%25203381.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffecf20d67%26DocId%3D7598361%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D5%26hits%3D6bb%2B6bc%2B6bd%2B6e2%2B6f1%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201898%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Evening%2520News%25201898%2520-%25203381.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffecf20d67%26DocId%3D7598361%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D5%26hits%3D6bb%2B6bc%2B6bd%2B6e2%2B6f1%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[The Buffalo Evening News]]''|date=4 June 1898|location=Buffalo, New York|page=3}}</ref> She remained in the west for several years, working with a western college, before returning to New York in 1905.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Elizabeth Marney Conner’s Work|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201905%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201905%2520a%2520-%25200436.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D3dcd242c%26DocId%3D6890500%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D6%26hits%3Da42%2Ba43%2Ba44%2Ba49%2Ba4a%2Ba4b%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201905%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201905%2520a%2520-%25200436.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D3dcd242c%26DocId%3D6890500%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D6%26hits%3Da42%2Ba43%2Ba44%2Ba49%2Ba4a%2Ba4b%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[Buffalo Courier-Express|The Buffalo Courier]]''|date=11 February 1905|location=Buffalo, New York|page=5}}</ref> A follower of [[Christian Science]], in 1906, in Buffalo, she was one of the founders of the International Progressive Thought League, along with [[Grace Carew Sheldon]]. She traveled to Detroit and established a Progressive Thought reading room there.<ref name="Buff Express (1931)">{{cite news|title=Elizabeth Marney Conner Is All for World Peace|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201931%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201931%2520-%25207524.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffb21125a7%26DocId%3D8199996%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D12%26hits%3Da%2Bb%2Bc%2B45%2B5a%2Bc2%2B106%2B14a%2B3e2%2B41c%2B4ab%2Bfa1%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201931%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201931%2520-%25207524.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffb21125a7%26DocId%3D8199996%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D12%26hits%3Da%2Bb%2Bc%2B45%2B5a%2Bc2%2B106%2B14a%2B3e2%2B41c%2B4ab%2Bfa1%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[Buffalo Courier-Express]]''|date=25 October 1931|location=Buffalo, New York|page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|editor1-last=Parkyn|editor1-first=Herbert A.|title=The international Progressive Thought League|journal=Suggestion|date=October 1906|volume=XVII|issue=2|pages=185–186|url=http://www.iapsop.com/archive/materials/suggestion/suggestion_v17_n4_oct_1906.pdf|location=Chicago, Illinois}}</ref>
Leaving Buffalo again, around 1909, Conner resumed her speaking and writing efforts, mainly throughout New York State.<ref name="Buff Express (1931)" /> She published a book ''The Golden Pomegranates of Eden'' which dealt with sex education<ref>{{cite news|title=Golden Pomegranates|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201908%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201908%2520-%25204447.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffa9e77d84%26DocId%3D9331423%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D4%26hits%3D405%2B406%2Bb38%2Be09%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201908%2FBuffalo%2520Ny%2520Courier%25201908%2520-%25204447.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffa9e77d84%26DocId%3D9331423%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D4%26hits%3D405%2B406%2Bb38%2Be09%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[Buffalo Courier-Express|The Buffalo Courier]]''|date=27 October 1908|location=Buffalo, New York}}</ref> and worked for fifteen years on a book ''The Moon Faery''. In 1931, she returned to Buffalo for its centennial celebration, advising that she was working and speaking as a peace activist.<ref name="Buff Express (1931)" /> At the time, she was living in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|title=Elizabeth M. Conner Sends Greetings to Buffalo Friends|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201930%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201930%2520-%25204104.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffb403ec30%26DocId%3D8057810%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D7%26hits%3Db94%2Bb96%2Bba5%2Bba6%2Bba7%2Bbc6%2Bbd8%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201930%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201930%2520-%25204104.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffb403ec30%26DocId%3D8057810%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D7%26hits%3Db94%2Bb96%2Bba5%2Bba6%2Bba7%2Bbc6%2Bbd8%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[Buffalo Courier Express]]''|date=27 December 1930|location=Buffalo, New York|page=9}}</ref> In 1932, she returned to Buffalo to speak at a Women’s Democratic Club meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Democratic Women Meet|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201932%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201932%2520-%25200878.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffba29ccd7%26DocId%3D8206333%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D3%26hits%3D35%2B36%2B799%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201932%2FBuffalo%2520NY%2520Courier%2520Express%25201932%2520-%25200878.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffba29ccd7%26DocId%3D8206333%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D3%26hits%3D35%2B36%2B799%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[Buffalo Courier-Express]]''|date=4 February 1932|location=Buffalo, New York|page=5}}</ref>
==Personal life== She was buried at Elmwood Cemetery, Burlington, Vermont.<ref name="findagrave.com">{{cite web|title=Elizabeth Marney Conner (1855 – ) – Find A Grave Memorial|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Conner&GSiman=1&GSst=49&GRid=23190640&|website=www.findagrave.com|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>
