{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Use Pakistani English|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox dancer | name = Maharaj Ghulam Hussain | image = | alt = | caption = | full_name = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1905 {{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} | birth_place = [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], [[India]] | death_date = 2001{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} | death_place = [[Lahore]], [[Pakistan]] | height = | occupation = [[Dancer]], [[teacher]] | years_active = | former_groups = | dances = [[Kathak]] | website = }}
'''Maharaj Ghulam Hussain Kathak''' (1905 &ndash; 2001) was a classical dancer and teacher.
==Early life== Ghulam Hussain was born in [[Calcutta]].{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} He was a Hindu who later converted - his early name of Maina].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110713181917/http://www.lahorechitrkar.com/view-artist.php?ID=81 ]</ref><ref>''The Encyclopedia of Pakistan'', editors Hafeez Malik, Yuri V. Gankovsky, [[Oxford University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0195977356}}</ref> Ghulam Hussain came to Pakistan in the 1960s.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} After staying in Karachi he moved to Lahore in 1971.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} He never performed in Pakistan.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} He was a disciple of Acchan Maharaj, the father of [[Birju Maharaj]] in India, who was a very well known performer.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} In a musical conference in Banaras in 1938, he was betstowed with the title "Maharaj Kathak" by his gurus, in the presence of singers and dancers.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}}
==Migration to Pakistan== Maharaj Ghulam Hussain Kathak migrated to [[Karachi]] after the partition and lived there before moving to Lahore in his later years. He has been a major exponent in the arts and teaching of classical [[kathak]] dance in Pakistan, for over four decades.<ref>Rainbow of music and dance: national [[performing arts]] group, Ayesha Taslim, [[Pakistan National Council of the Arts]]</ref> Maharaj also appeared in 1995 Pakistani musical film ''[[Sargam (1995 film)|Sargam]]'' directed by Syed Noor starring the singer [[Adnan Sami]] and his ex-wife [[Zeba Bakhtiar]]. This was followed by another appearance of Maharaj in a Pakistan Television play series.
== Legacy == Maharaj Ghulam Hussain Kathak was the guru of Pakistani classical dancer Nahid Siddiqui, [[Nighat Chaodhry]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFXkPk3zMeYC&pg=RA1-PA126&lpg=RA1-PA126&dq=Maharaj+Ghulam+Hussain+Kathak&source=bl&ots=oarTFT6sVV&sig=5ieCweOcLUE5kcFuajfsd6Fwia8&hl=en&ei=YAi1SoK7HIGqswP0yYDSDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9#v=onepage&q=Maharaj%20Ghulam%20Hussain%20Kathak&f=false |title=India's Kathak Dance, Past Present, Future |author=Reginald Massey |page=126|isbn=978-8170173748 |website=Books.google.com |date=1999-01-01 |accessdate=2016-12-24}}</ref><ref>''Old Roads, New Highways : Fifty Years of Pakistan'', Victoria Schofield, [[Oxford University Press]], 1997, {{ISBN|978-0195778458}}</ref><ref>''British Alternative Theatre Directory 1988'', David McGillivray, Robert Conway, Conway McGillivray, 1988, ASIN B00PAC01MA</ref> [[Fasih Ur Rehman]], a discipline of Ghulam Hussain, has been carrying on his legacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fasihurrehman.com/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517134949/http://fasihurrehman.com/ |archivedate=2014-05-17 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mag4you.com/spotlight/Fasih-Ur-Rehman/3648.htm |title=Latest Interview with Fasih-Ur-Rehman, Celebrity Online |website=Mag4you.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-24}}</ref>
